The Cartesian product of A and B, denoted as A × B, is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is in A and b is in B. 

A × B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

The Cartesian product of B and A, denoted as B × A, is the set of all ordered pairs (b, a) where b is in B and a is in A.

B × A = {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}

Now, let's take the union of A × B and B × A:

(A × B) ∪ (B × A) = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}

We can see that the elements in A × B are not the same as the elements in B × A, as the ordered pairs have different components. Therefore, A × B and B × A are not the same, and their union contains all the distinct ordered pairs from both sets.
